[2]
Date: Sat 17 Jan 2009
Source: Tempo (Manila), [edited]
<http://www.tempo.com.ph/news.php?aid=43854>


Ebola-infected farms still under quarantine
-------------------------------------------
Pending the final results conducted by CDC in Atlanta, Georgia, on the
reported discovery of the Ebola Reston virus (ERV), Department of
Agriculture secretary Arthur Yap directed to maintain the quarantine in the
2 farms as well as the voluntary export ban of raw and processed swine
products which he instituted in December [2008].

"We decided to keep the farms in quarantine and suspend the export of our
hogs until we have a better grasp of the extent, nature and consequences of
the Reston virus to the health of animals and humans," Yap explained.

This developed after the secretary Francisco Duque III of the Department of
Health sought the help of CDC. "I have directed RITM (Research Institute of
Tropical Medicine) to immediately send the collected samples from the 2
farms to CDC for testing and we expect the results to come out any time in
the next few weeks," Duque said.

The joint mission composed of experts in animal and human health from the
FAO, the OIE, the WHO and their national counterparts reported on the
progress of the mission last Wednesday [14 Jan 2009] in an executive
session with Yap and Duque. The mission was tasked to investigate the
recent discovery of the ERV in pigs in the Philippines.

During the past 10 days, they conducted risk assessment, field
investigations and collection of samples for laboratory testing in the 2
farms in Bulacan and Pangasinan where ERV was detected.

[byline: Jeamma E Sabate]

